            <!-- Stemmatics -->
            <note type="stemmatics">OY lists three mss., none of which are historic. There are some aspects which point towards its being by Ibn ‘Arabī. One ms. (Carullah 2070) quotes IA at the end: “I completed it in one day in Mosul,” and a work of this title is listed in both the lists which IA made of his own works, Fihris muʾallafāt al-shaykh al-akbar (RG142) and Ijāza li-l-malik al-Muẓaffar (RG 269). But Claude Addas has examined the text as it appears in the printed Cairo edition, and feels that the internal evidence of the text does not permit its attribution to Ibn ‘Arabī. Therefore, in the absence of further evidence, it is classified as unverified. Further mss identified by JC: Manchester, Rylands 106 X (1031H?); Riḍā (=Raza?) library, Rampur (India) 369/1 or SerialNo 3939; AccNo 8314; BookNo 997; ff.29b-41a (990H)</note>
